            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Connor Riley\u2019s sense of justice was forged not in the gleaming towers of San Francisco, but in the shadow of rusting steel mills in Scranton, Pennsylvania. The son of a union machinist and a public-school librarian, he grew up with a healthy distrust of corporate narratives and a deep respect for hard-won facts. His path was set early on, leading him to a journalism degree from Penn State, where he eschewed campus antics for long nights at the student paper, chasing down administrative mismanagement stories.\n\nHis early career was a tour of Pennsylvania\u2019s forgotten towns, writing for local papers where his reporting on municipal corruption earned him a name for being tenacious. The turning point came when a story about a local data-mining operation revealed its direct link to a powerful Silicon Valley tech giant. The investigation won him a regional award and, more importantly, a job offer from *The Bay Ledger*, a digital-first, investigative news outlet in San Francisco. He arrived at age 27, ready to take on the titans of tech.\n\nNow 37, Connor is a seasoned veteran of the city\u2019s information wars. His most significant investigation, a searing expos\u00e9 on privacy violations at a ubiquitous social media company, cemented his career but dismantled his personal life; his long-term partner couldn\u2019t endure the stress and shadowy threats that came with the story. The fallout left him cautious and more dedicated than ever to his work.\n\nConnor\u2019s life is contained within a small, walkable radius. He lives in a modest, rent-controlled apartment in North Beach, cherishing its grit and history as an antidote to the sleek, sterile world he so often covers. His daily 1.5-mile walk to his SoMa office is a ritual, a ground-level survey of the city\u2019s profound inequalities. His evenings are spent either chasing leads in quiet bars or decompressing with a small circle of trusted journalist friends. Connor\u2019s connection to San Francisco is one of a loving critic; he is fascinated by its innovative spirit but committed to holding its immense power accountable. His ultimate dream is to write a book that exposes the systemic flaws of the tech economy, a definitive work that outlasts the fleeting news cycle."
        },
