            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers his first night, age 27. Standing on a North Beach corner, he looked from the familiar brick of his building to the alien gleam of the Transamerica Pyramid. It wasn't wonder he felt, but a cold clarity. This was the new mill, the new powerhouse he had to dismantle with facts. The feeling wasn't excitement, but the heavy weight of a fight just begun. That moment solidified his identity as an outsider, a necessary critic in a city intoxicating itself with power.\n\n2.\nHe can still feel the electric jolt from that night, four years ago. It was 3 a.m. in the empty *Ledger* office when the anonymous source\u2019s final file downloaded: the internal memo explicitly ordering engineers to ignore privacy flags. Staring at the screen, a predatory stillness came over him. This was the kill shot. The feeling was pure, righteous victory, a high that confirmed his path while blinding him to the personal cost it would soon exact.\n\n3.\nThe memory that stings most isn't a threat, but the quiet that followed. A few months after his big expos\u00e9, age 35, his partner was packing a bag and said, \"Your crusade has no room for anyone else.\" The words were spoken without anger, just a deep, hollow exhaustion. He had no counterargument. In that moment, he realized his professional armor had become a personal cage, a lesson in collateral damage that made him forever cautious with his heart.\n\n4.\nOne evening last year, nursing a beer at Vesuvio Cafe, an old poet told him stories of Kerouac and the Beats. He watched the tourists outside, then looked at the worn-out wood of the bar and felt a profound sense of place. He wasn't just a tech reporter; he was part of a lineage of dissenters in that alley, a tradition of speaking truth to the city\u2019s latest gilded power. It was a comforting thought, a quiet anchor in his turbulent work.\n\n5.\nHis daily walk became a ritual about two years ago. He saw a man huddled in a doorway in the Financial District, using a faded \u2018Innovate Summit 2.0\u2019 tote bag to hold his few possessions. The brutal irony hit Connor like a physical blow. The city wasn\u2019t two worlds, but one, its obscene wealth and desperate poverty inextricably linked. That image fuels his walk every morning, a constant, nagging reminder of the story he is destined to write."
